34/* Store in OUTPUT a string (made with alloca) containing an
35 assembler-name for a local static variable or function named NAME.
36 LABELNO is an integer which is different for each call. */
37
38#ifndef ASM_PN_FORMAT
39# ifndef NO_DOT_IN_LABEL
40# define ASM_PN_FORMAT "%s.%lu"
41# else
42# ifndef NO_DOLLAR_IN_LABEL
43# define ASM_PN_FORMAT "%s$%lu"
44# else
45# define ASM_PN_FORMAT "__%s_%lu"
46# endif
47# endif
48#endif /* ! ASM_PN_FORMAT */
49
50#ifndef ASM_FORMAT_PRIVATE_NAME
51# define ASM_FORMAT_PRIVATE_NAME(OUTPUT, NAME, LABELNO) \
52 do { const char *const name_ = (NAME); \
53 char *const output_ = (OUTPUT) = \
54 (char *) alloca (strlen (name_) + 32); \
55 sprintf (output_, ASM_PN_FORMAT, name_, (unsigned long)(LABELNO)); \
56 } while (0)
57#endif
58
59/* Choose a reasonable default for ASM_OUTPUT_ASCII. */
60
61#ifndef ASM_OUTPUT_ASCII
62#define ASM_OUTPUT_ASCII(MYFILE, MYSTRING, MYLENGTH) \
63 do { \
64 FILE *_hide_asm_out_file = (MYFILE); \
65 const unsigned char *_hide_p = (const unsigned char *) (MYSTRING); \
66 int _hide_thissize = (MYLENGTH); \
67 { \
68 FILE *asm_out_file = _hide_asm_out_file; \
69 const unsigned char *p = _hide_p; \
70 int thissize = _hide_thissize; \
71 int i; \
72 fprintf (asm_out_file, "\t.ascii \""); \
73 \
74 for (i = 0; i < thissize; i++) \
75 { \
76 int c = p[i]; \
77 if (c == '\"' || c == '\\') \
78 putc ('\\', asm_out_file); \
79 if (ISPRINT (c)) \
80 putc (c, asm_out_file); \
81 else \
82 { \
83 fprintf (asm_out_file, "\\%o", c); \
84 /* After an octal-escape, if a digit follows, \
85 terminate one string constant and start another. \
86 The VAX assembler fails to stop reading the escape \
87 after three digits, so this is the only way we \
88 can get it to parse the data properly. */ \
89 if (i < thissize - 1 && ISDIGIT (p[i + 1])) \
90 fprintf (asm_out_file, "\"\n\t.ascii \""); \
91 } \
92 } \
93 fprintf (asm_out_file, "\"\n"); \
94 } \
95 } \
96 while (0)
97#endif

99/* This is how we tell the assembler to equate two values. */
100#ifdef SET_ASM_OP
101#ifndef ASM_OUTPUT_DEF
102#define ASM_OUTPUT_DEF(FILE,LABEL1,LABEL2) \
103 do { fprintf ((FILE), "%s", SET_ASM_OP); \
104 assemble_name (FILE, LABEL1); \
105 fprintf (FILE, ","); \
106 assemble_name (FILE, LABEL2); \
107 fprintf (FILE, "\n"); \
108 } while (0)
109#endif
110#endif

138/* This is how to output the definition of a user-level label named
139 NAME, such as the label on variable NAME. */
140
141#ifndef ASM_OUTPUT_LABEL
142#define ASM_OUTPUT_LABEL(FILE,NAME) \
143 do { \
144 assemble_name ((FILE), (NAME)); \
145 fputs (":\n", (FILE)); \
146 } while (0)
147#endif
148
149/* This is how to output the definition of a user-level label named
150 NAME, such as the label on a function. */
151
152#ifndef ASM_OUTPUT_FUNCTION_LABEL
153#define ASM_OUTPUT_FUNCTION_LABEL(FILE, NAME, DECL) \
154 ASM_OUTPUT_LABEL ((FILE), (NAME))
155#endif
156
157/* Output the definition of a compiler-generated label named NAME. */
158#ifndef ASM_OUTPUT_INTERNAL_LABEL
159#define ASM_OUTPUT_INTERNAL_LABEL(FILE,NAME) \
160 do { \
161 assemble_name_raw ((FILE), (NAME)); \
162 fputs (":\n", (FILE)); \
163 } while (0)
164#endif

166/* This is how to output a reference to a user-level label named NAME. */
167
168#ifndef ASM_OUTPUT_LABELREF
169#define ASM_OUTPUT_LABELREF(FILE,NAME) \
170 do { \
171 fputs (user_label_prefix, (FILE)); \
172 fputs ((NAME), (FILE)); \

185/* This is how we tell the assembler that a symbol is weak. */
186#ifndef ASM_OUTPUT_WEAK_ALIAS
187#if defined (ASM_WEAKEN_LABEL) && defined (ASM_OUTPUT_DEF)
188#define ASM_OUTPUT_WEAK_ALIAS(STREAM, NAME, VALUE) \
189 do \
190 { \
191 ASM_WEAKEN_LABEL (STREAM, NAME); \
192 if (VALUE) \
193 ASM_OUTPUT_DEF (STREAM, NAME, VALUE); \
194 } \
195 while (0)
196#endif
197#endif
198
199/* This is how we tell the assembler that a symbol is a weak alias to
200 another symbol that doesn't require the other symbol to be defined.
201 Uses of the former will turn into weak uses of the latter, i.e.,
202 uses that, in case the latter is undefined, will not cause errors,
203 and will add it to the symbol table as weak undefined. However, if
204 the latter is referenced directly, a strong reference prevails. */
205#ifndef ASM_OUTPUT_WEAKREF
206#if defined HAVE_GAS_WEAKREF
207#define ASM_OUTPUT_WEAKREF(FILE, DECL, NAME, VALUE) \
208 do \
209 { \
210 fprintf ((FILE), "\t.weakref\t"); \
211 assemble_name ((FILE), (NAME)); \
212 fprintf ((FILE), ","); \
213 assemble_name ((FILE), (VALUE)); \
214 fprintf ((FILE), "\n"); \
215 } \
216 while (0)
217#endif
218#endif
219
220/* How to emit a .type directive. */
221#ifndef ASM_OUTPUT_TYPE_DIRECTIVE
222#if defined TYPE_ASM_OP && defined TYPE_OPERAND_FMT
223#define ASM_OUTPUT_TYPE_DIRECTIVE(STREAM, NAME, TYPE) \
224 do \
225 { \
226 fputs (TYPE_ASM_OP, STREAM); \
227 assemble_name (STREAM, NAME); \
228 fputs (", ", STREAM); \
229 fprintf (STREAM, TYPE_OPERAND_FMT, TYPE); \
230 putc ('\n', STREAM); \
231 } \
232 while (0)
233#endif
234#endif
235
236/* How to emit a .size directive. */
237#ifndef ASM_OUTPUT_SIZE_DIRECTIVE
238#ifdef SIZE_ASM_OP
239#define ASM_OUTPUT_SIZE_DIRECTIVE(STREAM, NAME, SIZE) \
240 do \
241 { \
242 HOST_WIDE_INT size_ = (SIZE); \
243 fputs (SIZE_ASM_OP, STREAM); \
244 assemble_name (STREAM, NAME); \
245 fprintf (STREAM, ", " HOST_WIDE_INT_PRINT_DEC "\n", size_); \
246 } \
247 while (0)
248
249#define ASM_OUTPUT_MEASURED_SIZE(STREAM, NAME) \
250 do \
251 { \
252 fputs (SIZE_ASM_OP, STREAM); \
253 assemble_name (STREAM, NAME); \
254 fputs (", .-", STREAM); \
255 assemble_name (STREAM, NAME); \
256 putc ('\n', STREAM); \
257 } \
258 while (0)
259
260#endif
261#endif

317/* If the target supports weak symbols, define TARGET_ATTRIBUTE_WEAK to
318 provide a weak attribute. Else define it to nothing.
319
320 This would normally belong in ansidecl.h, but SUPPORTS_WEAK is
321 not available at that time.
322
323 Note, this is only for use by target files which we know are to be
324 compiled by GCC. */
325#ifndef TARGET_ATTRIBUTE_WEAK
326# if SUPPORTS_WEAK
327# define TARGET_ATTRIBUTE_WEAK __attribute__ ((weak))
328# else
329# define TARGET_ATTRIBUTE_WEAK
330# endif
331#endif

360/* On many systems, different EH table encodings are used under
361 difference circumstances. Some will require runtime relocations;
362 some will not. For those that do not require runtime relocations,
363 we would like to make the table read-only. However, since the
364 read-only tables may need to be combined with read-write tables
365 that do require runtime relocation, it is not safe to make the
366 tables read-only unless the linker will merge read-only and
367 read-write sections into a single read-write section. If your
368 linker does not have this ability, but your system is such that no
369 encoding used with non-PIC code will ever require a runtime
370 relocation, then you can define EH_TABLES_CAN_BE_READ_ONLY to 1 in
371 your target configuration file. */
372#ifndef EH_TABLES_CAN_BE_READ_ONLY
373#ifdef HAVE_LD_RO_RW_SECTION_MIXING
374#define EH_TABLES_CAN_BE_READ_ONLY 1
375#else
376#define EH_TABLES_CAN_BE_READ_ONLY 0
377#endif
378#endif

447/* The size of addresses as they appear in the Dwarf 2 data.
448 Some architectures use word addresses to refer to code locations,
449 but Dwarf 2 info always uses byte addresses. On such machines,
450 Dwarf 2 addresses need to be larger than the architecture's
451 pointers. */
452#ifndef DWARF2_ADDR_SIZE
453#define DWARF2_ADDR_SIZE ((POINTER_SIZE + BITS_PER_UNIT - 1) / BITS_PER_UNIT)
454#endif

456/* The size in bytes of a DWARF field indicating an offset or length

460#ifndef DWARF_OFFSET_SIZE
461#define DWARF_OFFSET_SIZE 4
462#endif

1295#ifdef GCC_INSN_FLAGS_H
1296/* Dependent default target macro definitions
1297
1298 This section of defaults.h defines target macros that depend on generated
1299 headers. This is a bit awkward: We want to put all default definitions
1300 for target macros in defaults.h, but some of the defaults depend on the
1301 HAVE_* flags defines of insn-flags.h. But insn-flags.h is not always
1302 included by files that do include defaults.h.
1303
1304 Fortunately, the default macro definitions that depend on the HAVE_*
1305 macros are also the ones that will only be used inside GCC itself, i.e.
1306 not in the gen* programs or in target objects like libgcc.
1307
1308 Obviously, it would be best to keep this section of defaults.h as small
1309 as possible, by converting the macros defined below to target hooks or
1310 functions.
1311*/
1312
1313/* The default branch cost is 1. */
1314#ifndef BRANCH_COST
1315#define BRANCH_COST(speed_p, predictable_p) 1
1316#endif
1317
1318/* If a memory-to-memory move would take MOVE_RATIO or more simple
1319 move-instruction sequences, we will do a movmem or libcall instead. */
1320
1321#ifndef MOVE_RATIO
1322#if defined (HAVE_movmemqi) || defined (HAVE_movmemhi) || defined (HAVE_movmemsi) || defined (HAVE_movmemdi) || defined (HAVE_movmemti)
1323#define MOVE_RATIO(speed) 2
1324#else
1325/* If we are optimizing for space (-Os), cut down the default move ratio. */
1326#define MOVE_RATIO(speed) ((speed) ? 15 : 3)
1327#endif
1328#endif
1329
1330/* If a clear memory operation would take CLEAR_RATIO or more simple
1331 move-instruction sequences, we will do a setmem or libcall instead. */
1332
1333#ifndef CLEAR_RATIO
1334#if defined (HAVE_setmemqi) || defined (HAVE_setmemhi) || defined (HAVE_setmemsi) || defined (HAVE_setmemdi) || defined (HAVE_setmemti)
1335#define CLEAR_RATIO(speed) 2
1336#else
1337/* If we are optimizing for space, cut down the default clear ratio. */
1338#define CLEAR_RATIO(speed) ((speed) ? 15 :3)
1339#endif
1340#endif
1341
1342/* If a memory set (to value other than zero) operation would take
1343 SET_RATIO or more simple move-instruction sequences, we will do a movmem
1344 or libcall instead. */
1345#ifndef SET_RATIO
1346#define SET_RATIO(speed) MOVE_RATIO (speed)
1347#endif
1348
1349/* Supply a default definition for FUNCTION_ARG_PADDING:
1350 usually pad upward, but pad short args downward on
1351 big-endian machines. */
1352
1353#define DEFAULT_FUNCTION_ARG_PADDING(MODE, TYPE) \
1354 (! BYTES_BIG_ENDIAN \
1355 ? upward \
1356 : (((MODE) == BLKmode \
1357 ? ((TYPE) && TREE_CODE (TYPE_SIZE (TYPE)) == INTEGER_CST \
1358 && int_size_in_bytes (TYPE) < (PARM_BOUNDARY / BITS_PER_UNIT)) \
1359 : GET_MODE_BITSIZE (MODE) < PARM_BOUNDARY) \
1360 ? downward : upward))
1361
1362#ifndef FUNCTION_ARG_PADDING
1363#define FUNCTION_ARG_PADDING(MODE, TYPE) \
1364 DEFAULT_FUNCTION_ARG_PADDING ((MODE), (TYPE))
1365#endif

1368 Normally move_insn, so Pmode stack pointer. */
1369
1370#ifndef STACK_SAVEAREA_MODE
1371#define STACK_SAVEAREA_MODE(LEVEL) Pmode
1372#endif

1374/* Supply a default definition of STACK_SIZE_MODE for
1375 allocate_dynamic_stack_space. Normally PLUS/MINUS, so word_mode. */
1376
1377#ifndef STACK_SIZE_MODE
1378#define STACK_SIZE_MODE word_mode
1379#endif

1381/* Default value for flag_stack_protect when flag_stack_protect is initialized to -1:
1382 --enable-default-ssp: Default flag_stack_protect to -fstack-protector-strong.
1383 --disable-default-ssp: Default flag_stack_protect to 0.
1384 */
1385#ifdef ENABLE_DEFAULT_SSP
1386# ifndef DEFAULT_FLAG_SSP
1387# define DEFAULT_FLAG_SSP 3
1388# endif
1389#else
1390# define DEFAULT_FLAG_SSP 0
1391#endif

1393/* Provide default values for the macros controlling stack checking. */
1394
1395/* The default is neither full builtin stack checking... */
1396#ifndef STACK_CHECK_BUILTIN
1397#define STACK_CHECK_BUILTIN 0
1398#endif
1399
1400/* ...nor static builtin stack checking. */
1401#ifndef STACK_CHECK_STATIC_BUILTIN
1402#define STACK_CHECK_STATIC_BUILTIN 0
1403#endif
1404
1405/* The default interval is one page (4096 bytes). */
1406#ifndef STACK_CHECK_PROBE_INTERVAL_EXP
1407#define STACK_CHECK_PROBE_INTERVAL_EXP 12
1408#endif
1409
1410/* The default is not to move the stack pointer. */
1411#ifndef STACK_CHECK_MOVING_SP
1412#define STACK_CHECK_MOVING_SP 0
1413#endif
1414
1415/* This is a kludge to try to capture the discrepancy between the old
1416 mechanism (generic stack checking) and the new mechanism (static
1417 builtin stack checking). STACK_CHECK_PROTECT needs to be bumped
1418 for the latter because part of the protection area is effectively
1419 included in STACK_CHECK_MAX_FRAME_SIZE for the former. */
1420#ifdef STACK_CHECK_PROTECT
1421#define STACK_OLD_CHECK_PROTECT STACK_CHECK_PROTECT
1422#else
1423#define STACK_OLD_CHECK_PROTECT \
1424 (!global_options.x_flag_exceptions \
1425 ? 75 * UNITS_PER_WORD \
1426 : targetm_common.except_unwind_info (&global_options) == UI_SJLJ \
1427 ? 4 * 1024 \
1428 : 8 * 1024)
1429#endif
1430
1431/* Minimum amount of stack required to recover from an anticipated stack
1432 overflow detection. The default value conveys an estimate of the amount
1433 of stack required to propagate an exception. */
1434#ifndef STACK_CHECK_PROTECT
1435#define STACK_CHECK_PROTECT \
1436 (!global_options.x_flag_exceptions \
1437 ? 4 * 1024 \
1438 : targetm_common.except_unwind_info (&global_options) == UI_SJLJ \
1439 ? 8 * 1024 \
1440 : 12 * 1024)
1441#endif
1442
1443/* Make the maximum frame size be the largest we can and still only need
1444 one probe per function. */
1445#ifndef STACK_CHECK_MAX_FRAME_SIZE
1446#define STACK_CHECK_MAX_FRAME_SIZE \
1447 ((1 << STACK_CHECK_PROBE_INTERVAL_EXP) - UNITS_PER_WORD)
1448#endif
1449
1450/* This is arbitrary, but should be large enough everywhere. */
1451#ifndef STACK_CHECK_FIXED_FRAME_SIZE
1452#define STACK_CHECK_FIXED_FRAME_SIZE (4 * UNITS_PER_WORD)
1453#endif
1454
1455/* Provide a reasonable default for the maximum size of an object to
1456 allocate in the fixed frame. We may need to be able to make this
1457 controllable by the user at some point. */
1458#ifndef STACK_CHECK_MAX_VAR_SIZE
1459#define STACK_CHECK_MAX_VAR_SIZE (STACK_CHECK_MAX_FRAME_SIZE / 100)
1460#endif

1462/* By default, the C++ compiler will use function addresses in the
1463 vtable entries. Setting this nonzero tells the compiler to use
1464 function descriptors instead. The value of this macro says how
1465 many words wide the descriptor is (normally 2). It is assumed
1466 that the address of a function descriptor may be treated as a
1467 pointer to a function. */
1468#ifndef TARGET_VTABLE_USES_DESCRIPTORS
1469#define TARGET_VTABLE_USES_DESCRIPTORS 0
1470#endif
